msDesc.head: Theological miscellany: Alain de Lille, Hugo Argentinensis, Pseudo-Augustine

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, 1-23A, 23B-115. : older modern foliation, 89-119, struck out. mundum domini qui conditor

collation.signatures:
The manuscript exhibits four types of contemporary quire signatures, suggesting that the different parts of the manuscript were assembled and rebound already in the middle ages: quire 1 is unmarked; quire 2, is marked by an abbreviated secundus inside a square frame in red (), the only signature of this kind. Quire 3 is marked with tertius written out (), and quire 4 with iiiius
written on the first folio of the quire (), possibly in the same hand, and possibly also on its last folio (). These quires transmit the Ars praedicatoria by Alain of Lille, and the quire numbers agree with the current structure. Quires 5-8, which transmit four collections of glosses and excerpts, seem once to have made up a separate unit: the signatures exhibit two layers, of which the first consists of Roman ordinal numerals, Ius
to IIIIus
, in red ( (erased), , , ), in front of which a second, contemporary hand has added v (IIIIus
is simply crossed out and the second hand has added IXus
instead). These numbers are, however, ahead by one compared to the current structure. Quire 9, beginning the Liber soliloquiorum by Psuedo-Augustine, is simply numbered as XIus
in the same hand as the second layer of 5-8 (); the number X is thus missing from the signatures, indicating that one full quire has been lost. The texts which remain are, however, complete.

p.note: Top left corner, in black ink over 2 lines by an early modern hand: No 195 Brocmanni; upper centre page, in black ink by an early modern hand over 11 lines: a list of contents; centre right, in black ink in Brocman's hand: a note dating the manuscript to 1360; bottom centre, also in Brocman's hand: cf. Serm. Amici in 4o Bas. 1495; bottom left margin, in pencil by a modern hand: the current signum; bottom right corner: National Library book label with the current signum.

binding.p:
Medieval binding. Brown leather over bevelled wooden boards. 5 double raised bands and endbands. Hooked clasps and leather straps. , in black ink: 195
; stamped in gold: A 106.
binding.condition: Leather worn. One clasp missing and half of the second clasp. The leather straps are dry and stiff.

history.origin:
14th century, second half. The script used in the first two codicological units, cursiva antiquior, is mainly seen in Austria, Bohemia, Germany and Scandinavia, and does not occur before the second quarter of the 14th century; few examples exist, according to Derolez, after the beginning of the 15th century ( Derolez (2006)
). The mix of double- and single-compartment a seen in the last part of the manuscript identifies this as a late variant of the script. The colophon on gives the year for the completion of this section, and Brocman, in a note on , dates the manuscript to based on the type of paper. Brocman's note on , identifiying the contents as explanation of the difficult words in the Breviarium Upsalense, would seem to indicate Uppsala? as the origin.
history.provenance: Previously no. 195 in the collection of Nils Reinhold Brocman, book collector and librarian at the Royal Library and Antiquities Archive. Upon his death in , a large part of his book collection was donated to the Antiquities Archive (SBL).
history.acquisition: Transferred to the National Library from the Antiquities Archive.

msItem.title: De arte praedicatoria
msItem.explicit: a qua morte idem ipse christus nos liberare dignetur qui cum patre et filio et spiritu sancto viuit et regnat per infinita secula seculorum Amen
msItem.note: Due to leaves missing, the text begins in the middle of the prologue, after which follows a table of contents. The rubrics and text agree in large part with the text printed by Migne; however, the last chapter, Ad somnolentos, is missing from the manuscript. Instead, two chapters are listed which are not found in Migne; the last chapters of the text consist of sermons.

note.p: Lemmata, underlined in red, and glosses are presented in running text. Neither every psalm nor every verse of the psalms is included.

msItem.title: Exposition of the Decalogue
msItem.incipit: Si in preceptis meis ambulaueritis (Lev. 26:3) Secuntur decem precepta domini
msItem.explicit: Sodomitis offensoribus clerorum hereticis non confessis AMEN
msItem.note: The exposition ends with a concordance between the ten commendments and the ten plagues of Egypt, and after this a number of tables listing, with their definitions, the ten commandments, the seven cardinal sins, and the works of mercy.

note.p: A brief treatise on penance and episcopal and papal absolution with excerpts from Gratian's Decretals.
